I know your original post was regarding Oakland Flyers out of the GA runway
at OAK, but since I too, live in San Francisco I wanted to mention that you
might want to consider Reid-Hillview in San Jose.  I make the drive everyday
and it is about 45 minutes in good traffic (I use 280 so there is almost
always a good no-stop drive all the way to my home airport).

The main reason I mention RHV (Reid-Hillview Airport) in San Jose is that it
has many advantages - the main one is that most of our days are usually
flyable and not plagued by the issues with fog and low overcast that OAK and
some of the GA airports North of us, often experiences because of  their
proximity to the bay.  Having more flyable days will translate to more
steady progress in your primary training.   The other beauty of flying out
of RHV is that we sit beneath a convenient 'cut-out' of San Jose
International's Class C airspace.  What this means is that we have a
instructional environment where we can bring a student into the slightly
more complex communication challenges of  dealing with the Class C airspace
when the student is ready.  Until then we have plenty of airspace where we
can focus on training the rudiments of learning to fly, just east and south
of of our airport.  RHV being a Class D airport means that you will have
experience dealing with a towered airport, right from the start.

There are several flight schools at our airport; Nice Air (where I fly and
instruct), Tradewinds Aviation, Squadron 2 and, last but not least, Amelia
Reid Aviation (which focuses on learning to fly in tailwheel aircraft ((that
is instead of the tricycle gear aircraft that have a nosewheel))).

So, though you may have been thinking about Oakland (dealing with the fog
and Bay Bridge traffic) you might want to consider RHV in San Jose.  I
should mention that further down 101 south there is San Carlos Airport and
Palo Alto Airport, the only 'problem' with these two airports is that they
are more often affected by fog and that crosswinds are more the norm than
the exception.   Although a certain amount of your training will definitely
be focused on crosswind technique, it is a bit much for an early hour
student to be dealing with right from the 'get-go'.  At RHV, more often than
not,  most of our training days have a wind coming pretty much straight down
the runway most of the time and when it comes to crosswind practice we can
always head off to a nearby airport and get plenty of that when you are
ready.

Anyway, hope you will check our airport out as I think you'll find the
advantages far outweigh those of the airport you are currently considering.

