I just wanted to add (forgot to do so in my first reply post to you) that
'ground' or 'home study' for the written exam, et al, is more determined by
'you'.   I mean to say that if you aren't one of those people who can
dedicate themselves to a course of study and prefer to study in group
settings then home study may not be for you.  If you're like me, you welcome
the new learning and have no problem setting aside the time to study (after
all you're getting to learn about something you've likely been wanting to do
as long as you can remember - how cool is that!?).

Everyone is likely to have their own preference regarding home study
materials but it is my opinion that nothing beats the King Schools written
test courses (as well as some of their other training materials) for
teaching you in a manner that you will remember and retain.  I've tried
others, Sportys, etc.. but (for me) nothing has worked for me (in terms of
studying for the written exam) like the King Schools materials have.

Now having said the latter, keep in-mind that you'll want some books to
study with.  Although the instructor you choose may have a preference on the
text book you use, there is nothing that says that you can have (within
reason &lt;grin&gt;) too many books that you are reading.  Although it is not
'perfect' I have become a big fan of the Rod Machado Private Pilot book and
would strongly recommend that you purchase it with his workbook to further
supplement your learning.  I like his book, in that it is well-illustrated
and will give you a very well-rounded study book, overall.   The only thing
I slight it for, in parts, is he'll stick with one or two analogies too long
when I feel he could transition the student to the concept at that point.  A
good example is his water analogy of electrical current and devices; it
works and is a good idea initially, I just would prefer he gradually
transition the student from that water analogy and move forward on the
subject from there.  There are just a few other items like that, but all
certainly minor concerns with this very 'chock-full' of information training
resource.   The Jeppesen texts are also quite good as well.

Anyway, hope this helps and you've come to the right newsgroup as there is a
bunch of people who love to fly and enjoy helping someone achieve their
dream of flight.  I've been with this group from my early student
instruction and all the way through my CFI.

