Hi Dado,

I don't know anything about Oakland Flyers personally, but here are
some of my thoughts based on looking at their Web site:
- The rates are really good.  I'm paying $95/hour plus a $6/hour fuel
surcharge at my club for the same type of plane that rents for $75/hour
at Oakland Flyers.  However, I don't see any mention of whether the
rates are "wet" or "dry".  "Wet" rates include fuel and "dry" rates
don't.  Obviously wet rates (like what I'm paying) are more expensive
than dry rates.  Find out if their rates are wet or dry.
- The Web site doesn't state that they offer liability insurance for
their renters.  Some clubs (mine include) provide this for their
members.  if Oakland Flyers doesn't provide this, then that will be an
added expense.
- I like that Oakland Flyers has a "pay as you go" plan.  Personally, I
wouldn't lock myself into something where I had to pay a whole bunch of
money up front.  I also like that they give you a discount for paying
$500 up front.  I tended to do that anyway with my instructor, and I
wish he had given me a 10% discount for that. :^)
- They've got an on-line scheduling system -- that's a plus.  Actually,
I take that back -- that's a requirement in this day and age.
- Don't believe the cost estimates that they give you.  Actually -
don't believe any of the cost estimates that clubs provide on the Web.
It will most likely take you more than 40 hours dual and 10 hour solo
to learn how to fly (in my case, it took around 120 hours dual and 25
hours solo, but it probably took me longer than average).   Also, it
looks  like some of the numbers they have there are out of date.  For
example, I spent $110 (not $85) on my last medical exam and $80 (not
$75) for the written exam.

The best way to pick a club is to go to the airport, talk to the people
there, take an introductory flight, and look at the aircraft they have
to offer.    Look to see if they're well maintained.  I think the most
important thing to look for in a club is good maintenance.  If they
don't maintain their aircraft well, then there's no point in flying
them.  A club is really just the people that run the club and the
planes that you fly, so if you like both, then I should think it will
work out.

Now I'm going to plug my own club . . . :^)  Take a look at West Valley
Flying Club ( www.wvfc.org ).  They operate out of the San Carlos, Palo
Alto, Hayward, and South County airports.  They're a bit farther away
from San Francisco than Oakland, but not as far as San Jose, although
we do get lots of the crosswinds and fog that Cecil mentions (nothing
like trying to learn how to land a plane with a 10-knot crosswind
blowing).  :^)

-- Bryan

(P.S.  If you do end up in San Carlos and/or at West Valley, give me a
holler).
