Lou Fields, CFII at the Old T's on North Field -- a nice guy, an
aquaintance of mine at Oakland (I used to rent his lovely old 1966 Arrow
every now and then -- the checkride he did with me before he let me rent
it was both amusing and instructive -- he's a fund of good stories, but
he's also sharp as hell while instructing). He used to fly off carriers
in the Pacific during WWII, and was a DE until a few years ago -- in
fact he was going to be the DE for my instrument rating but was ill so I
ended up with Rich Bachelder, another, erm, character who I rather like.
But unfortunately he's basically sold pretty much all his own aircraft
and given up on instructing as far as I can tell.

I'd agree with Mr Campbell on Oakland Flyers -- not bad overall, and if
you can get a good instructor (I can recommend one in particular),
pretty good. I fly mostly with California Airways at Hayward nowadays,
and I recommend them with the usual caveats about getting a good
instructor, but that's probably pushing it for you from San Francisco.

