I'll let Mr Campbell give you that one... Bachelder's the source of or
subject of a great many stories, and is something of a character (he was
once in the Navy, then a cop in Berkeley, and he has, erm, lots of
strong opinions -- but I got on with him quite well).

On my own instrument checkride with him I actually got into an argument
with him while under the hood: he asked me to do something dumb with the
GPS and I blurted out something along the lines of "you can't do that!
It just doesn't work that way!". He persisted for a while while I
struggled to maintain the hold (or whatever) under the hood over the
Sacramento Delta somewhere near Rio Vista and attempted to explain why
with this particular unit it wouldn't work, and I finally just told him
we'd do it my way or we'd either still be in the hold in an hour's time
arguing over it or we'd be somewhere out over the Pacific when I'd
proved him wrong and would never see dry land again. He was quite
gracious about it and spent much of the rest of the flight kidding me
about it and asking me questions about why we Brits and Aussies
pronounced things the way we did (I have what to US ears is a strong
British accent) or why we called autopilots "George" and that sort of
thing. A stressful but ultimately oddly enjoyable checkride.

